for Aya Hijazi and her husband,
Mohamed Hassanein.

09:59.098 --> 10:04.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The apartment they just moved
into outside
Washington is still sparsely
furnished, but

10:04.670 --> 10:10.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's a place to call their own,
and it's a
world away from the Egyptian
jail cells and

10:10.610 --> 10:15.114 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
crowded courtroom cages they
were kept in
for three years.

10:15.147 --> 10:20.319 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They had met in Tahrir Square in
the heady
days after Egypt's 2011
revolution.

10:20.353 --> 10:26.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI, Released Charity
Worker: Initially,
it seemed like the political
climate to allow

10:26.492 --> 10:28.327 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for political change.

10:28.361 --> 10:33.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But by 2013,
after the military
deposed the Muslim Brotherhood
government,

10:33.899 --> 10:35.534 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the picture darkened.

10:35.568 --> 10:37.570 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They looked to build a little
light.

10:37.603 --> 10:43.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: And so it seemed
like the only
venue to actually do change and
give hope

10:43.342 --> 10:48.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and not be -- not vilify or be
vilified is
to work on humanitarian causes
that no other

10:48.848 --> 10:51.651 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
two people could differ on,
like, say, children.

10:51.684 --> 10:53.853 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Who would want a child to sleep
in the streets?

10:53.886 --> 10:59.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: In an Orwellian
twist, the
organization they founded to
help those children

10:59.425 --> 11:04.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
would lead to heinous unfounded
charges of
child abuse and human
trafficking.

11:04.697 --> 11:06.799 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: We still don't
really know what
happened.

11:06.832 --> 11:10.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Like, we know the picture, but
we don't not
why or how.

11:10.236 --> 11:14.573 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The kids started to love us and
really tell
each other about our
organization.

11:14.607 --> 11:20.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And everything was going on
smoothly, until
one day supposedly a father came
looking for

11:20.379 --> 11:27.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
his son, whom we have never seen
and the children
have never seen, and we went
with him to file

11:27.787 --> 11:33.492 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a police report, because he was
quite abusive
with us and the NGO and the
children.

11:33.526 --> 11:37.630 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And instead of us filing a
report, we found
that we are charged with human
trafficking.

11:37.663 --> 11:40.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, there had
been no indication
before that of a problem?

11:40.800 --> 11:42.101 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
AYA HIJAZI: No.

11:42.134 --> 11:44.170 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And were you
immediately taken
into custody?

11:44.203 --> 11:46.439 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: Yes, from that day
on.

11:46.472 --> 11:48.941 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How did you deal
with it?

11:48.974 --> 11:52.078 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You were separated pretty
immediately, is
that right?

11:52.111 --> 11:53.079 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
AYA HIJAZI: Yes.

11:53.112 --> 11:54.613 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

11:54.647 --> 12:00.286 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we couldn't contact anyone,
but the word
got through very, very quickly.

12:00.319 --> 12:02.688 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so lawyers came, but they
weren't ours.

12:02.722 --> 12:05.057 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They were just volunteers.

12:05.091 --> 12:09.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I just thought that,
immediately, when
I talk to a prosecutor or a
judge, we will

12:09.361 --> 12:13.165 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
be released within a day or a
few days.

12:13.199 --> 12:15.835 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And it went on for three years.

12:15.868 --> 12:21.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Three years
shuttled from different
prisons to court appearances,
the newly married

12:21.807 --> 12:25.411 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
couple seeing each other only
fleetingly.

12:25.444 --> 12:29.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How much were you able to be in
contact with
each other during the time you
were held?

12:29.281 --> 12:33.753 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: It was very hard to
get letters
across, through our families.

12:33.786 --> 12:36.489 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Our families would visit us,
exchange letters.

12:36.522 --> 12:40.726 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Other than that, we would wait
for court sessions
to meet.

12:40.760 --> 12:45.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it's like, a total of 18
months, we saw
each other only three times and
maybe only

12:45.131 --> 12:46.699 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for a minute, or less even.

12:46.732 --> 12:48.434 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Tell me about
your experience.

12:48.467 --> 12:54.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: I wasn't tortured in
prison or
beaten or even -- I didn't
receive abusive

12:54.774 --> 12:56.442 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
words.

12:56.475 --> 13:00.112 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was very hard for me that I
was placed
with regular crimes.

13:00.146 --> 13:04.350 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Like, I wasn't even classified
inside the
prison as political prisoners.

13:04.383 --> 13:09.488 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I was like the charges were
very heinous,
like raping children.

13:09.522 --> 13:12.358 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so it was very hard just
coping with that.

13:12.391 --> 13:16.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MOHAMED HASSANEIN, Released
Charity Worker
(through translator): Prison
itself is against

13:16.562 --> 13:18.397 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
human nature.

13:18.430 --> 13:22.535 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The idea of prison is that it
takes away from
the person's humanity and the
person's ideas.

13:22.568 --> 13:27.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But if the person was able to
keep his or
her core ideas and humanity,
then the person

13:27.072 --> 13:28.841 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
has won.

13:28.874 --> 13:33.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Aya taught
herself French and
Spanish while in prison and she
learned to

13:33.779 --> 13:35.514 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
draw.

13:35.548 --> 13:40.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She showed me one pencil sketch
that reflected
what she said was her own
experience.

13:40.219 --> 13:41.287 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Where are you in this drawing?

13:41.320 --> 13:45.558 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: I find myself in a
lot of those.

13:45.591 --> 13:50.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Like, I find myself here, like,
all right,
come, I'm ready to go to prison
just to prove

13:50.729 --> 13:52.498 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
my point.

13:52.531 --> 13:56.802 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I find myself here looking at
the window,
seeing the streets and wishing
that I could

13:56.836 --> 13:58.704 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
be part of it one day again.

13:58.737 --> 14:02.641 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Is it true that
most of the
people in Egypt don't know
what's going on

14:02.675 --> 14:04.143 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
inside prison?

14:04.176 --> 14:09.582 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: Yes, prisons are
largely a closed
place, and we suffered that.

14:09.615 --> 14:15.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: While they
endured, unbeknownst
to them, Aya and Mohamed had
many advocates

14:15.454 --> 14:18.424 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on the outside, and many in high
places.

14:18.457 --> 14:20.259 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

14:20.292 --> 14:22.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCO RUBIO (R), Florida: I
would like to
raise the case of
Egyptian-American citizen

14:22.828 --> 14:24.597 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Aya Hijazi.

14:24.630 --> 14:28.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Were you aware
that President
Obama was trying to get you out
of prison?

14:28.467 --> 14:33.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: I know that the
administration
towards the end was involved and
did a lot.

14:33.405 --> 14:37.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was towards the end of our
imprisonment
and towards the end of their
administration

14:37.276 --> 14:42.581 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that they have -- and I have to
give credit
where credit is due, so I am
thankful to them.

14:42.615 --> 14:43.782 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, that
happened.

14:43.816 --> 14:46.118 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then a new president comes
into office.

14:46.151 --> 14:50.222 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And how did you hear that he was
working on
this?

14:50.256 --> 14:53.125 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what we saw was, he said
something to
President El-Sisi.

14:53.158 --> 14:54.960 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, how did you hear about all
this?

14:54.994 --> 15:02.668 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: So, in Egypt, we --
in the prison,
we got to see some newspapers.

15:02.701 --> 15:10.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so Trump was saying that
they shouldn't
be discussing human rights
issues publicly.

15:10.342 --> 15:13.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It seemed like it's being
discussed, but behind
closed doors.

15:13.412 --> 15:19.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And then how did
you learn
that something might happen,
that you might

15:19.752 --> 15:21.587 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
be freed?

15:21.620 --> 15:25.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: So, we knew that
there was American
interest, but up until the last
day, we had

15:25.891 --> 15:29.662 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
no idea how it will go, until
the day of the
acquittal.

15:29.695 --> 15:30.663 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It was a surprise.

15:30.696 --> 15:31.664 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Until the final
day?

15:31.697 --> 15:32.665 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
AYA HIJAZI: Yes.

15:32.698 --> 15:33.899 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, how did you
learn?

15:33.933 --> 15:35.734 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What -- how did you learn?

15:35.768 --> 15:44.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: It was actually in
the cage where
the judge acquitted us all, and
it was -- it

15:44.443 --> 15:46.211 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
was unbelievable.

15:46.245 --> 15:50.582 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Like, we prayed for it so much,
but we thought
it's far-reaching, like the best
that could

15:50.616 --> 15:52.084 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
be done is a pardon.

15:52.117 --> 15:54.119 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we were really hoping we
wouldn't reach
that.

15:54.153 --> 15:55.988 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And it was a surprise.

15:56.021 --> 15:59.558 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You literally had
no preparation
for when you were -- the judge
told you, OK,

15:59.591 --> 16:00.559 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
you are acquitted.

16:00.592 --> 16:01.760 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
AYA HIJAZI: Yes.

16:01.794 --> 16:04.797 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We didn't know that he would say
acquitted,
in a sense.

16:04.830 --> 16:07.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was like the best moment of
our lives,
all of us.

16:07.566 --> 16:12.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: That moment just
six weeks
ago came after President Trump's
meeting in

16:12.671 --> 16:17.242 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Washington with Egypt's
President Abdel Fattah
El-Sisi.

16:17.276 --> 16:22.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mr. Trump has made a point of
befriending
Sisi and has been highly
complimentary of

16:22.214 --> 16:25.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
him, following years of strained
relations
with the Obama administration.

16:25.818 --> 16:29.355 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP, President of the
United States:
And I just want to say to you,
Mr. President,

16:29.388 --> 16:33.459 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that you have a great friend and
ally in the
United States and in me.

16:33.492 --> 16:38.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Aya's view of Mr.
Trump's praise
of the Egyptian leader are
complicated.

16:38.964 --> 16:46.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: This is difficult
for me, because
I don't share his view on Mr.
Sisi.

16:46.839 --> 16:49.375 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I could differ with Mr. Trump.

16:49.408 --> 16:56.482 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I would like to actually
direct this to
Mr. Sisi, if he listens.

16:56.515 --> 16:59.885 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It wasn't just us who were
imprisoned, unjustly
imprisoned.

16:59.918 --> 17:05.657 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if Mr. Sisi had a role, or
if -- I would
tell you, Mr. Sisi, if you had a
role then,

17:05.691 --> 17:09.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
then that's good, but there are
thousands
and thousands of wrongly
imprisoned people.

17:09.995 --> 17:14.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Almost
immediately upon her
release, a U.S. government plane
whisked Aya

17:14.833 --> 17:21.640 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and Mohamed to the United
States, where Aya
soon sat with the president in
the Oval Office,

17:21.673 --> 17:26.211 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
the same chair in which
President Sisi had
sat a few weeks earlier.

17:26.245 --> 17:32.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: We are happy to
have Aya back
home, and it's a great honor to
have her in

17:32.985 --> 17:34.219 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the Oval Office.

17:34.253 --> 17:36.021 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How was your
meeting with President
Trump?

17:36.055 --> 17:39.425 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
AYA HIJAZI: He was very
hospitable.

17:39.458 --> 17:43.429 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He made us feel very welcome,
and he admired
our strength.

17:43.462 --> 17:45.230 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I work for the children.

17:45.264 --> 17:46.465 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
So, I was glad.

17:46.498 --> 17:48.667 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What did he ask
you?

17:48.700 --> 17:53.372 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: Oh, one of the
questions he asked
was about the time of my arrest.

17:53.405 --> 17:58.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he like -- I'm not sure, but
it seemed
like he had this idea that -- or
a conviction

17:58.043 --> 17:59.845 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that it was at the time of the
Muslim Brotherhood.

17:59.878 --> 18:01.580 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Which was before
President
El-Sisi.

18:01.613 --> 18:03.115 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: Which was before
Sisi.

18:03.148 --> 18:05.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, he was like, "So was your
arrest -- be
at the time of the Brotherhood?"

18:05.150 --> 18:06.518 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And I said, no.

18:06.552 --> 18:09.755 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then he said, "Oh, it was at
the time
of Sisi."

18:09.788 --> 18:12.658 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And he was taken aback.

18:12.691 --> 18:14.560 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It seemed, like, different to
what he had
in mind.

18:14.593 --> 18:18.630 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Is there a
contradiction between
President Trump working to get
you released

18:18.664 --> 18:25.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and, on the other hand, praising
the government
of Egypt which was holding you
in prison?

18:25.537 --> 18:35.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: I think he's trying
to be effective,
because he even said it to me
while we met,

18:35.547 --> 18:40.552 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
that, well, that he was
effective, wasn't
he?

18:40.586 --> 18:44.823 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I don't know how to say no.

18:44.857 --> 18:49.628 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So there is the traditional way
of just, like,
mere criticism, very sharp
criticism, and

18:49.661 --> 18:51.663 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there is the more diplomatic
way, perhaps.

18:51.697 --> 18:58.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Do you think that
maybe, in
your conversation with him and
in his learning

18:58.604 --> 19:04.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about your experience, that
maybe he's -- you
have adjusted his thinking about
human rights?

19:04.676 --> 19:06.845 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Or what do you think about that?

19:06.879 --> 19:14.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: I hope he gets to
know that the
human rights situation is really
horrible

19:15.020 --> 19:21.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at that time, and people are not
just -- it's
not just for fighting terrorism,
because people

19:21.994 --> 19:25.464 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are unjustly held, and there are
so many fabricated
cases.

19:25.497 --> 19:27.232 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They are illegitimately held.

19:27.266 --> 19:30.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Are both of you
optimistic
that things are going to get
better in Egypt?

19:30.502 --> 19:33.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MOHAMED HASSANEIN (through
translator): Worry
and optimism are different
things.

19:33.705 --> 19:37.676 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's very normal to be worried,
but it's not
normal to live out hope.

19:37.709 --> 19:39.011 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And we're also hopeful.

19:39.044 --> 19:40.379 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And I'm worried.

19:40.412 --> 19:44.049 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What do you want
for Egypt,
for the people of Egypt?

19:44.082 --> 19:45.450 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What do you want for them?

19:45.484 --> 19:48.954 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: We want what we call
-- some may
call American values.

19:48.987 --> 19:55.093 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I would like to think of them as
universal
values, humanity, number one, a
good governed

19:55.127 --> 20:00.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
state where people can express
themselves,
where they can freely assemble,
where they

20:00.799 --> 20:02.601 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
can live in harmony and peace.

20:02.634 --> 20:05.070 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Democracy is not a bad word to
describe that.

20:05.103 --> 20:06.805 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you believe
that time is
coming?

20:06.838 --> 20:12.911 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AYA HIJAZI: We have to believe
until the very
last day we die.

20:12.945 --> 20:18.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, if we want to be parents
-- we're
not parents yet -- and we want
to see something

20:18.417 --> 20:20.185 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
good for future generations.

20:20.219 --> 20:31.630 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So either we say we have given
you a better
world, or we die trying.

20:31.663 --> 20:38.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: President
Trump spent the
last full day of his first and
lengthy overseas

20:38.503 --> 20:42.574 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
trip in Sicily today at a
meeting of the so-called
G7 countries.

20:42.608 --> 20:47.646 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It ended a week that took him
from Saudi Arabia,
to Israel and the West Bank, to
the Vatican,

20:47.679 --> 20:51.383 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and yesterday to the Brussels
headquarters
of the European Union and NATO.

20:51.416 --> 20:55.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I spoke a short time ago with
Bloomberg News
White House correspondent
Margaret Talev in

20:55.554 --> 21:00.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Taormina, Sicily, and asked her
if President
Trump tried to convey central
messages to

21:00.492 --> 21:01.560 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
world leaders.

21:01.593 --> 21:04.029 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARGARET TALEV, Bloomberg News:
There sure
were.

21:04.062 --> 21:08.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I would say, in the Middle East,
it was the
idea that President Trump is
uniquely qualified

21:08.433 --> 21:12.804 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to restart the Mideast peace
process by kind
of shifting the focus a little
bit away from

21:12.838 --> 21:18.710 align:left position:25%,start line:73.33% size:75%
that traditional
Israeli-Palestinian dynamic
to this broader idea of Israelis
and Muslim

21:18.744 --> 21:22.614 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and Arab nations having a lot in
common in
a desire to fight terrorism.

21:22.648 --> 21:23.849 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's one big message.

21:23.882 --> 21:25.884 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
In Europe, the message really
was different.

21:25.917 --> 21:31.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it was sort of bringing
President Trump's
campaign promises about kind of
resetting

21:31.857 --> 21:39.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
expectations for NATO countries,
paying what
he would call their fair share,
rebalancing

21:39.164 --> 21:43.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
trade and how Europe and the
United States
think about trade with one
another, the idea

21:43.802 --> 21:47.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of reciprocal trade agreements,
if you make
this tough for me, I will make
this tough

21:47.939 --> 21:49.107 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
for you.

21:49.141 --> 21:52.110 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Those were a lot of those
messages in Western
Europe.

21:52.144 --> 21:55.547 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, so, I think what you saw
pretty much
follows.

21:55.580 --> 22:03.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was a very warm welcome in
the Middle East,
and a much sort of more
skeptical, sometimes

22:03.955 --> 22:07.659 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
critical reception in at NATO
and the G7.

22:07.693 --> 22:10.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Tell us about
a little bit
about those reactions from world
leaders,

22:10.162 --> 22:11.930 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
at least on the European side.

22:11.963 --> 22:17.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET TALEV: Yes, I mean, the
visit with
the pope, of course, it was sort
of how President

22:17.302 --> 22:19.905 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Trump kicked off his arrival in
Europe.

22:19.938 --> 22:26.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we know, from the last
year's campaign,
how many differences of opinion
the two men

22:26.611 --> 22:28.413 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
have.

22:28.447 --> 22:34.519 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so both of their teams sort
of made clear
from the outset that this was an
attempt for

22:34.553 --> 22:39.558 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
each to preserve a channel to
talk with one
another, but that they weren't
going to be

22:39.591 --> 22:41.860 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
necessarily on the same page
about everything.

22:41.893 --> 22:46.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Trump's reaction,
ebullient, joyous,
great honor, love it, grinning
ear to ear.

22:46.998 --> 22:53.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Pope Francis' demeanor, much
more reserved,
and a lot of sort of reading on
the tea leaves

22:53.205 --> 22:54.506 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and the body language on that
front.

22:54.539 --> 22:56.808 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We will see where that
relationship goes.

22:56.842 --> 23:03.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, from there, the move over
to NATO, the
Western allies in NATO had sort
of boxed him

23:03.915 --> 23:08.787 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
in to try to force his
commitment, for him
to restate a commitment to NATO
by having

23:08.820 --> 23:14.126 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
him attend this unveiling of an
Article 5
memorial.

23:14.159 --> 23:20.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And President Trump was willing
to be led
to the water to a point, but to
choose his

23:20.198 --> 23:25.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
wording carefully in terms of
reaffirming
his commitment to Article 5
without saying,

23:25.337 --> 23:28.240 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and I'm in it forever no matter
what, you
know, whatever you need.

23:28.273 --> 23:30.142 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That wasn't the message.

23:30.175 --> 23:35.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The message was very much,
Article 5, we appreciate
that it was invoked for the U.S.
after 9/11,

23:36.014 --> 23:42.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but for NATO to work long-term,
there needs
to be a stepping up of financial
contributions.

23:42.687 --> 23:46.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That was -- the NATO leaders
have already
agreed to that.

23:46.324 --> 23:48.260 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There have been plans made three
years ago.

23:48.293 --> 23:50.095 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This was always on track to be
stepped up.

23:50.128 --> 23:53.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A lot of those leaders really
bristled at
the idea that President Trump
was trying to

23:53.999 --> 23:57.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
say this was all because of him
and some bad
feelings there.

23:57.235 --> 24:02.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then, as you moved over to
the G7, two
big issues rolling into the
final day of the

24:02.707 --> 24:08.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
summit that have emerged as
fairly predictable
stumbling blocks again are
climate change

24:08.313 --> 24:10.048 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and trade.

24:10.081 --> 24:15.487 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Angela Merkel, the German
leader, telling
folks after day one's session
that all of

24:15.520 --> 24:21.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the other leaders of the G7 were
unanimous
in pressing the president of the
United States

24:21.593 --> 24:25.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to stay with Paris and to get
sort of with
their program.

24:25.197 --> 24:30.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Gary Cohn, the president's
economic adviser,
preserving the space for
President Trump perhaps

24:30.402 --> 24:35.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to stay in the Paris talks, to
show that he's
listening to European leaders,
but leaving

24:35.774 --> 24:40.779 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a little bit of room to do that
at his own
pace and under his own terms,
and saying,

24:40.812 --> 24:42.013 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
look, I want to get this right.

24:42.047 --> 24:45.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm going to take my time,
meaning not necessarily
here.

24:45.917 --> 24:51.957 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then on trade, again, we're
expecting
months, if not longer, of kind
of a shift

24:51.990 --> 24:57.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in discussions about what the
future of U.S.
and European trade relations are
going to

24:57.596 --> 24:59.464 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
look like.

24:59.498 --> 25:01.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And we also
saw a very short
communique out of the G7,
usually a sign that

25:01.199 --> 25:05.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there was very little that they
all agreed
on to put on paper.

25:05.136 --> 25:06.972 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARGARET TALEV: Yes, that's
right.

25:07.005 --> 25:08.840 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, you can say that that's
a good thing.

25:08.874 --> 25:10.408 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You can say that it's a bad
thing.

25:10.442 --> 25:12.310 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You're not going to agree to
more than you
agree on.

25:12.344 --> 25:18.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this does, again, preserve
some diplomatic
space for moving closer together
in the future,

25:18.817 --> 25:21.786 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but it also reflects what sort
of visit this
was.

25:21.820 --> 25:26.558 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was calibrated by the White
House to show
that, to a domestic audience, as
well as to

25:26.591 --> 25:31.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Europe, that President Trump is
not going
to abandon every position that
he held from

25:31.796 --> 25:37.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the campaign just because he is
here in these
meetings, but, at the same time,
a recognition

25:37.402 --> 25:44.976 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from his aides that the more he
engages with
key allies all over the world,
the more nuance

25:45.010 --> 25:50.515 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is brought to the table in terms
of him understanding
the leadership role that the
U.S. is expected

25:50.549 --> 25:53.718 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to fulfill and the complexities
of those obligations.

25:53.752 --> 25:56.488 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Margaret Talev
of Bloomberg joining us tonight
from Italy,

25:56.521 --> 25:57.489 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
thanks so much.

25:57.522 --> 25:58.490 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARGARET TALEV: Thanks, Hari.

25:58.523 --> 26:10.035 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Stay with us.

