Coming up on the "NewsHour":
from the "NewsHour"
Bookshelf, a humorous take on
getting out

26:14.539 --> 26:20.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of your bubble; a soldier's
perspective on
being a veteran of a war that
never ends;

26:20.545 --> 26:25.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and what happened when one of
Mr. Roger's
neighbors met the TV icon during
a difficult

26:25.450 --> 26:28.286 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
season of life?

26:28.320 --> 26:30.322 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But first to the analysis of
Shields and Brooks.

26:30.355 --> 26:33.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's syndicated columnist Mark
Shields and
New York Times columnist David
Brooks.

26:33.758 --> 26:37.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
All right, let's start this week
on the foreign
front.

26:37.329 --> 26:42.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The president met potentates,
presidents,
prime ministers and a pope.

26:42.067 --> 26:43.935 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There were magical orbs.

26:43.969 --> 26:45.503 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

26:45.537 --> 26:47.505 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: There were
tweet-sized messages
stuck into a Wailing Wall.

26:47.539 --> 26:48.506 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
How did he do?

26:48.540 --> 26:49.507 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: B-plus.

26:49.541 --> 26:50.508 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
No.

26:50.542 --> 26:51.610 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

26:51.643 --> 26:52.510 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Well, I'm not
going to grade
him.

26:52.544 --> 26:54.112 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I grade him on the curve.

26:54.145 --> 27:03.521 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I would say the visual highlight
was with
the pope when he said, you know,
the pope

27:03.555 --> 27:08.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is a very humble man, much like
me, which
he had tweeted earlier, and
that's why I like

27:08.593 --> 27:10.362 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
him so much.

27:10.395 --> 27:14.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But just sort of they're polar
opposites,
of the two, one a champion of
immigrants and

27:14.666 --> 27:22.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
refugees and almost disdainful
of opulence
and excessive wealth, and the
other sort of

27:22.574 --> 27:24.376 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the embodiment of it.

27:24.409 --> 27:28.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I thought, quite frankly,
the first part
of the trip, he laid down the
policy, and

27:28.813 --> 27:35.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the policy is that we will stand
on the side
of Sunni autocrats against
terrorism, and

27:35.420 --> 27:37.155 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
no questions asked.

27:37.188 --> 27:43.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And here, in addition, is a
major weapons,
a huge weapons sale that -- and
we're not

27:43.795 --> 27:48.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
going to ask how you use it or
where you use
it, and if people are killed in
Yemen, and

27:48.767 --> 27:54.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they're -- made in the USA is on
the weapon
that kills them, and it's done
indiscriminately,

27:54.272 --> 27:59.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that's their business and not
ours, because
the operating and organizing
principle of

27:59.411 --> 28:03.648 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
foreign policy is opposition to
terrorism
under Donald Trump.

28:03.682 --> 28:06.918 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes, I thought
Melania had a
very good week.

28:06.951 --> 28:08.687 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I thought a lot of good moments
for her.

28:08.720 --> 28:10.655 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
There was a lot of good
judgments, actually.

28:10.689 --> 28:14.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He, by the standards of some of
the competence
of the previous week, I would
say you would

28:14.592 --> 28:18.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have to say the trip was, by
competence standards,
a success.

28:18.196 --> 28:22.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He did what he wanted to do in
Saudi Arabia,
at NATO, at various other
places.

28:22.434 --> 28:28.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I do think, as Mark suggested,
the chief oddity
of the entire trip is that we
seem to be mean

28:28.373 --> 28:31.609 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to our friends and kind to our
foes.

28:31.643 --> 28:35.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, Saudi Arabia -- Fareed
Zakaria had
a very good column on this --
we're supposed

28:35.947 --> 28:40.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to be against terrorism, and
Trump loves to
talk about Iranians -- Iran's
influence on

28:40.752 --> 28:45.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
terrorism, but the main source
of terror funding
for both the ideas and sometimes
the organizations

28:45.790 --> 28:46.758 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is Saudi Arabia.

28:46.791 --> 28:48.860 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's not Iran.

28:48.893 --> 28:51.463 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so -- but, somehow, we're
super nice to
Saudi Arabia.

28:51.496 --> 28:59.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Meanwhile, we're super mean to
Germany and
France and some of our NATO
allies.

28:59.104 --> 29:03.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so there's just been a
perversion of American
foreign policy, which is sort of
based on

29:03.842 --> 29:07.712 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the idea that character doesn't
matter, and
you can -- whether the leaders
from Russia

29:07.746 --> 29:13.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or the Philippines or Saudi
Arabia, that people
of bad character are people we
can ally with.

29:13.518 --> 29:16.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, somehow, I think there is a
consistency
between the government here and
some of the

29:17.021 --> 29:19.557 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
governments the Trump
administration likes
around the world.

29:19.591 --> 29:21.126 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: There was a
bit of that
we just saw...

29:21.159 --> 29:22.127 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: Yes.

29:22.160 --> 29:23.895 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I'm sorry?

29:23.928 --> 29:24.329 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: There was a
bit of that
we just saw in the conversation
that Judy

29:24.362 --> 29:25.330 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
had.

29:25.363 --> 29:27.232 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: That's exactly
right.

29:27.265 --> 29:31.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I would just say that the NATO
part of the
visit, I found particularly
disturbing, because

29:31.836 --> 29:35.473 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there was nothing about the
principles and
values.

29:35.507 --> 29:41.813 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There was nothing about values
and what we
share and what animates us and
what we respect

29:41.846 --> 29:46.217 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
and revere, whether it's
individual rights
or democracy.

29:46.251 --> 29:49.988 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
That just seemed to be
unimportant.

29:50.021 --> 29:57.095 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And all the criticism that the
president had
was stored up, as David pointed
out, for these

29:57.128 --> 29:59.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
folks for somehow being welfare
cheats or
something.

29:59.998 --> 30:00.999 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes.

30:01.032 --> 30:02.834 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that's pure demagoguery.

30:02.867 --> 30:07.438 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He spoke as if we -- they owe us
money because
they haven't been paying their
dues, which

30:07.472 --> 30:08.439 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is not true.

30:08.473 --> 30:10.108 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: Yes.

30:10.141 --> 30:11.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: That's not the way
that the
-- the problem is that they sort
of pledged

30:11.543 --> 30:13.845 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to gradually get to 2 percent of
GDP in defense
spending.

30:13.878 --> 30:15.547 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: That's right.

30:15.580 --> 30:17.215 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: And some of the
countries have,
and a lot of the countries have
not.

30:17.248 --> 30:19.017 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that's a legitimate issue.

30:19.050 --> 30:22.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But he portrayed it as if we're
bailing them
out, and they owe us money, and
they haven't

30:22.787 --> 30:24.856 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
paid their bills, which is just
actually untrue.

30:24.889 --> 30:27.792 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
let's shift gears
to the budget.

30:27.826 --> 30:30.628 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
What do you make of the
priorities that were
set forth in this?

30:30.662 --> 30:34.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a political document, but
it kind of
lets you know what you think is
important.

30:34.666 --> 30:37.035 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: That's right.

30:37.068 --> 30:41.639 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We don't pass a budget, but I
think it's fair
to say it was mean---spirited
and dishonest

30:41.673 --> 30:49.214 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were the two words that come
quickest to mind,
again, coming back to the visit
with the pope,

30:49.247 --> 30:55.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who has sort of made himself the
pope of the
poor, unlike a number of his
predecessors,

30:55.720 --> 30:59.991 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who seemed to enjoy the opulence
of Vatican
City.

31:00.024 --> 31:05.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Donald Trump, at that very
meeting, his
budget, which he is distanced
from, he's not

31:05.396 --> 31:14.272 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
even in town as it's released,
is, I think
fair to say, an orthodox
Republican document

31:14.305 --> 31:21.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the worst sense, in that it
is tax cuts
for the most advantaged among
us, and saving

31:21.779 --> 31:27.518 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the character of those Americans
who are struggling,
who depend upon school lunches,
who depend

31:27.552 --> 31:32.790 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
upon supplemental food, who
depend upon Medicaid
-- there are more people in the
United States

31:32.824 --> 31:35.426 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on Medicaid than there are on
Medicare.

31:35.460 --> 31:41.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And half of the people on
Medicaid get -- work
every day.

31:41.266 --> 31:43.401 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we're talking about elderly
poor.

31:43.434 --> 31:47.472 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, I mean, all of this is
being cut, for
what purpose?

31:47.505 --> 31:51.676 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To provide an enormous tax cut
for those who
are best-off.

31:51.709 --> 31:56.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: David, doesn't
some of this
go right at the base of
supporters that Donald

31:56.547 --> 32:00.251 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Trump have, the poor working
class that came
to him?

32:00.285 --> 32:03.688 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And it seems, as Mark is
pointing out, that
some of the programs that are
being cut are

32:03.721 --> 32:05.556 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
going to affect them first.

32:05.590 --> 32:08.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Well, you look at
the food stamps
program, and that has radically
expanded over

32:09.027 --> 32:10.962 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the last 10 years.

32:10.995 --> 32:14.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so the question is, has it
expanded maybe
for some of the reasons Social
Security disability

32:14.966 --> 32:18.136 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
expanded, just because it's
become sort of
welfare through the backdoor?

32:18.169 --> 32:19.971 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Is it illegitimate?

32:20.004 --> 32:23.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, if you look into the food
stamp program,
the reason it's expanded is
because a lot

32:23.408 --> 32:27.412 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of people are now near poor and
because of
economic changes.

32:27.445 --> 32:30.381 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It's not because of some
illegitimate explosion
of the welfare state.

32:30.415 --> 32:34.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's because of the underlying
structure of
society has disadvantaged a lot
of people,

32:34.519 --> 32:36.421 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and they need some help.

32:36.454 --> 32:40.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so it's -- as Donald Trump's
own secretary
of agriculture said, it's a
successful program,

32:40.925 --> 32:43.761 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and yet it's getting savagely
cut.

32:43.795 --> 32:48.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that's -- and that,
as you say,
goes right at the Trump voters,
because the

32:48.433 --> 32:52.470 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
lower-middle-class voters in
rural areas are
getting a lot of those benefits.

32:52.503 --> 32:58.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To me, the most egregious, two
egregious things
about the budget is, as Mark
said, it hurts

32:58.543 --> 33:03.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the poor and helps the rich, but
it also hurts
the young and helps the old, and
that whether

33:03.648 --> 33:07.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's food stamps or a lot the
other programs,
if you believe in human capital,
that we're

33:07.952 --> 33:12.857 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
investing in the future with a
lot these programs,
then that's the good kind of
spending, even

33:12.890 --> 33:14.692 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
if you're kind of conservative.

33:14.726 --> 33:18.129 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, to me, we should cut some
of the money
that goes to affluent elderly
people and give

33:18.162 --> 33:19.964 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
more money to young, struggling
people.

33:19.998 --> 33:21.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But Donald Trump does the
reverse.

33:21.899 --> 33:27.839 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the second thing is just the
almost in-your-face
dishonesty of it.

33:27.872 --> 33:32.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some of it is -- just it's
assuming there
will be 3 percent growth, which
is not going

33:32.243 --> 33:34.078 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to happen, given our
demographics.

33:34.112 --> 33:40.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But Larry Summers pointed out
that this made
the most elementary budget
calculating error

33:40.718 --> 33:43.021 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of any administration in 40
years.

33:43.054 --> 33:47.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They took the same revenue
source, and they
counted it twice, in order to
cover.

33:47.658 --> 33:51.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's just -- everybody had
the to catch
that error, but they were just
going to do

33:51.729 --> 33:53.031 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it anyway, and they didn't care
what anybody
said.

33:53.064 --> 33:55.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Larry Summers,
the former
treasury secretary.

33:55.500 --> 33:58.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, what about the president
coming back
and saying, hey, you know what,
I made these

33:58.870 --> 34:02.707 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
promises, I said I wasn't going
to touch aid
to the elderly?

34:02.740 --> 34:06.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Well, he said he
wouldn't cut
Social Security, Medicare or
Medicaid.

34:06.711 --> 34:13.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That was the promise he made in
one of his
campaign tweets, that I'm the
only candidate.

34:13.217 --> 34:15.253 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He made that point.

34:15.286 --> 34:16.921 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And he has not.

34:16.954 --> 34:18.856 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He has not touched Social
Security.

34:18.890 --> 34:26.531 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He's cutting SSI, Social
Security -- the Supplemental
Social Security, for people who
are disabled

34:26.564 --> 34:31.436 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and elderly, but he's not
cutting Social Security
payments to the elderly.

34:31.469 --> 34:36.507 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's not means-testing it in any
way, and
nor is he touching Medicare.

34:36.541 --> 34:40.111 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But Medicaid, having promised
not to, he is.

34:40.144 --> 34:41.579 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He is, in fact.

34:41.612 --> 34:46.617 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's almost -- cutting Medicaid,
proposed
to cut it in half, the spending.

34:46.651 --> 34:48.453 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Federal spending would be cut in
half.

34:48.486 --> 34:51.622 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the food stamps will be cut
by one-quarter.

34:51.656 --> 34:58.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I don't know how you justify
this when,
in the same week, Hari, the
Congressional

34:58.796 --> 35:05.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Budget Office, the Republican
selected chief
economist, but very respected
nonpartisan,

35:05.503 --> 35:11.342 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
says 23 million people are going
to lose the
health coverage insurance that
they already

35:11.375 --> 35:15.947 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have under the Republican-passed
plan.

35:15.980 --> 35:17.748 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I will say this unequivocally.

35:17.782 --> 35:23.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, three weeks after the
House passed
that health care bill, there is
not a single

35:23.187 --> 35:26.357 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
member of the House who regrets
having voted
against it.

35:26.390 --> 35:27.758 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What about
members of the
Senate?

35:27.792 --> 35:29.160 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What do they do going forward?

35:29.193 --> 35:31.062 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes, well, they're
going to
have trouble.

35:31.095 --> 35:35.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
First, it was kind of surprising
they went
through all the change of
rewriting the thing,

35:35.099 --> 35:38.336 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and they basically got the same
CBO number
as they got last time.

35:38.369 --> 35:40.938 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And I can't believe -- I
couldn't believe
they got so many House people to
vote for

35:40.972 --> 35:44.242 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this thing, because it's going
to be a killer
issue for a lot of people.

35:44.275 --> 35:48.045 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In the Senate, they're doing
everything in
secret right now.

35:48.079 --> 35:49.380 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: Yes.

35:49.413 --> 35:51.015 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: And so we don't
exactly know
what's happening.

35:51.048 --> 35:52.850 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They're talking with each other.

35:52.884 --> 35:56.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we do know they're divided
almost down
the middle on some of the
Medicaid cuts, on

35:56.954 --> 36:00.091 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
some oft other issues, on some
of the preexisting
conditions.

36:00.124 --> 36:04.095 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And passage in the Senate, you
wouldn't want
to bet on that, not by a long
shot.

36:04.128 --> 36:06.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And whatever
gets through
the Senate, there's a good
chance it wouldn't

36:06.564 --> 36:07.532 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
get passed in the House.

36:07.565 --> 36:08.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: Right.

36:08.566 --> 36:09.534 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It wouldn't get passed.

36:09.567 --> 36:11.369 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: Yes.

36:11.402 --> 36:16.107 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that, in order to make
it acceptable
-- the pledge to repeal
Obamacare was great

36:16.140 --> 36:18.176 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
as a political rallying cry.

36:18.209 --> 36:19.744 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's terrible policy.

36:19.777 --> 36:21.812 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And it's not -- it won't pass.

36:21.846 --> 36:25.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: But they could --
if they could
get -- they could have another
way to give

36:26.017 --> 36:30.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people health insurance through
health savings
accounts and tax credits and
things like that,

36:30.221 --> 36:33.124 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
if they guaranteed the same
level of coverage
that Obama is doing.

36:33.157 --> 36:35.660 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think that would be a
completely legitimate
approach.

36:35.693 --> 36:37.328 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Maybe introduce some more
competition into
the system.

36:37.361 --> 36:39.096 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That is not what they're doing.

36:39.130 --> 36:41.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
lastly, in the
last two minutes we have here, a
new member

36:41.933 --> 36:47.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the House of -- Republicans
-- during a
special election in Montana,
Greg Gianforte

36:47.905 --> 36:52.610 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
beats his opponents, but
body-slams a reporter
on the way to getting there.

36:52.643 --> 36:56.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What does this say about -- you
know, and
the thing that I heard this
morning on NPR

36:56.581 --> 36:59.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is, one of the reporters was
talking to some
of his supporters, saying, you
know what,

36:59.217 --> 37:01.085 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that guy had it coming.

37:01.118 --> 37:06.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, the extent of hostility
toward the
press and how it's manifesting
itself in different

37:06.090 --> 37:08.459 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ways in the past couple of
months.

37:08.492 --> 37:10.361 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: I don't think
there is any question.

37:10.394 --> 37:17.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it was legitimized in
part by President
Trump's campaign, which included
this and

37:17.201 --> 37:24.208 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sort of rhetorical excesses and
singling out
members of the press.

37:24.242 --> 37:30.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But Frank Luntz, the Republican
pollster,
who was the pollster for the
Contract With

37:31.015 --> 37:35.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
America, Newt Gingrich, said, if
you check
the party affiliation of someone
who commits

37:35.953 --> 37:41.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
assault before deciding how you
feel about
it, you're what's wrong with
America.

37:41.692 --> 37:43.594 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's really what it's
become.

37:43.628 --> 37:49.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the seminal moment in
contemporary
American politics was when
President Obama

37:49.767 --> 37:54.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was addressing the joint session
of Congress
on health care, and Joe Wilson
of South Carolina

37:54.105 --> 38:00.645 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
stood up and said, "You lie,"
unprecedented
in its rudeness and boorishness,
and he raised

38:00.678 --> 38:03.781 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a million dollars in the next
week in funds.

38:03.814 --> 38:05.983 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think that polarization
was rewarded.

38:06.017 --> 38:06.984 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes.

38:07.018 --> 38:08.719 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I would say two things are true.

38:08.753 --> 38:11.622 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The climate of ugliness is no
doubt ratcheting
up and giving some permission to
this.

38:11.656 --> 38:13.491 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In this case, I'm willing to
give the guy
a break.

38:13.524 --> 38:14.492 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He did apologize.

38:14.525 --> 38:16.027 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And he could have just lost his
temper.

38:16.060 --> 38:18.029 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We will see what his career is
like.

38:18.062 --> 38:23.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I'm willing to -- if a
leader is at least
willing to apologize, that's
frankly a step

38:23.134 --> 38:25.369 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
up from what we have seen on the
presidential
level.

38:25.403 --> 38:28.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right, New
York Times
columnist David Brooks,
syndicated columnist

38:28.406 --> 38:31.442 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Mark Shields, thank you both.

38:31.475 --> 38:35.046 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Thank you, Hari.

