38:52.797 --> 38:54.598 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
W. KAMAU BELL: And what do you
think about
that?

38:54.632 --> 38:57.735 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Sociopolitical
comedy, it's
a way of describing the work of
W. Kamau Bell,

38:57.768 --> 39:02.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
host of CNN's "United Shades of
America,"
in which he does something
rather unusual

39:02.073 --> 39:07.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
these days, seeking out the
America and Americans
we don't know or regularly
interact with.

39:07.912 --> 39:08.846 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
W. KAMAU BELL: Come here.

39:08.879 --> 39:10.214 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Come here.

39:10.247 --> 39:11.082 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: Can you say it, because
-- can you
tell me a little bit?

39:11.115 --> 39:12.283 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
W. KAMAU BELL: No, what you said
is true.

39:12.316 --> 39:13.284 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
All lives should matter.

39:13.317 --> 39:14.285 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WOMAN: I know that.

39:14.318 --> 39:15.586 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

39:15.619 --> 39:16.287 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
W. KAMAU BELL: But right now,
but not -- right
now, lives...

39:16.320 --> 39:17.254 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WOMAN: ... offensive.

39:17.288 --> 39:18.255 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

39:18.289 --> 39:19.256 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
It does.

39:19.290 --> 39:20.257 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

39:20.291 --> 39:21.258 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
W. KAMAU BELL: Yes.

39:21.292 --> 39:23.027 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
No.

39:23.060 --> 39:24.261 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, to many people it does,
because all
lives don't really matter in the
same way,

39:24.295 --> 39:24.962 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and then all lives matter is
like an aspirational
goal.

39:24.995 --> 39:26.931 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
White people, learn from her.

39:26.964 --> 39:31.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Now Bell expands
on his own
view of the world in a new book,
"The Awkward

39:31.535 --> 39:38.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Thoughts of W. Kamau Bell," with
the subtitle
"Tales of a 6' 4", African
American, Heterosexual,

39:38.242 --> 39:44.348 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Cisgender, Left-Leaning,
Asthmatic, Black
and Proud Blerd, Mama's Boy,
Dad, and Stand-Up

39:44.382 --> 39:45.349 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Comedian."

39:45.383 --> 39:46.350 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
So, welcome.

39:46.384 --> 39:47.351 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That says it all pretty much

39:47.385 --> 39:48.352 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
W. KAMAU BELL: Yes.

39:48.386 --> 39:49.353 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's the whole book.

39:49.387 --> 39:50.354 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: That's the book.

39:50.388 --> 39:51.522 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
W. KAMAU BELL: That's the book.

39:51.555 --> 39:52.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: We don't have to
read the book
anymore.

39:52.390 --> 39:53.357 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
W. KAMAU BELL: Yes.

39:53.391 --> 39:55.025 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

39:55.059 --> 39:56.894 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: "Awkward
Thoughts," though,
the title, what does that mean
exactly?

39:56.927 --> 39:58.629 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
W. KAMAU BELL: It comes from the
fact that
I realize that the best things
that have happened

39:58.662 --> 40:02.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to me in life have been friends
of mine sitting
me down and having awkward talks
with me,

40:02.366 --> 40:06.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
family members, or reading
things that challenge
me, that that's when I feel
really like I'm

40:06.704 --> 40:09.306 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
growing as a person, when I'm in
an awkward
situation.

40:09.340 --> 40:13.010 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And a lot of times, in society,
we're trained
to run from awkward situations.

40:13.043 --> 40:17.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If things get awkward, you
either run from
them or yell over them to try to
control them.

40:17.648 --> 40:20.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, for me, when things get
awkward, I get
quieter and start to listen
more.

40:20.451 --> 40:24.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I used that
sociopolitical
comedy, which I took from the
jacket cover

40:24.355 --> 40:26.524 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the book, so I assume you
approve of that.

40:26.557 --> 40:27.725 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
W. KAMAU BELL: Oh, yes.

40:27.758 --> 40:28.893 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
No, I'm the one who started
describing myself
as that.

40:28.926 --> 40:30.428 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You started that,
but what
does that mean?

40:30.461 --> 40:33.597 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
W. KAMAU BELL: I think I found
it somewhere,
this idea of sociopolitical.

40:33.631 --> 40:37.468 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A lot of times, a comedian like
me is a called
a political comedian.

40:37.501 --> 40:42.406 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think political comedy in
America conjures
up a pretty specific image.

40:42.440 --> 40:46.477 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I love political comedians,
but I think
there is a pretty big difference
between what

40:46.510 --> 40:49.280 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm doing and what you would
think a stand-up
political comedian is doing.

40:49.313 --> 40:51.649 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm talking about -- I'm not
talking much
about politicians.

40:51.682 --> 40:56.787 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I'm talking about social
movements or people
who are struggling or oppressed
people.

40:56.821 --> 40:59.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's not so much about what's
going on in
D.C.

40:59.390 --> 41:04.361 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In the television
show and
to some extent certainly in the
book, this

41:04.395 --> 41:06.430 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
search for the other, right?

41:06.464 --> 41:08.199 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
W. KAMAU BELL: Mm-hmm.

41:08.232 --> 41:11.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: One of the
premises clearly
is we're all in our own boxes,
and we need

41:11.869 --> 41:12.837 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to get out of them.

41:12.870 --> 41:14.705 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
W. KAMAU BELL: Yes.

41:14.738 --> 41:16.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The first part, when I was a
kid, I just moved
around a lot because my mom
moved around a

41:16.774 --> 41:18.476 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
lot.

41:18.509 --> 41:21.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think I sort of was
already being -- I
was always being broken out of
boxes.

41:21.979 --> 41:23.080 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
My dad lives in Alabama.

41:23.113 --> 41:25.015 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So we would be somewhere and go
to Alabama.

41:25.049 --> 41:28.686 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if you're in the north or in
the west
and you go to Alabama, that's a
different

41:28.719 --> 41:30.287 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
box.

41:30.321 --> 41:33.891 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, for me, the whole thing has
been about
like searching for where I
belong.

41:33.924 --> 41:37.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then, as an adult, as a
stand-up comedian,
you travel around the country
doing stand-up

41:37.728 --> 41:39.563 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
shows.

41:39.597 --> 41:41.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you go anywhere where they
will hire you,
so you're in different places
you never would

41:41.765 --> 41:46.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
think to go, like Garden City,
Kansas, or
Appalachian State University.

41:46.136 --> 41:48.873 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, for me, it's just been a
natural thing.

41:48.906 --> 41:52.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then the TV show sort of
takes all that
experience and really pushes it
forward another

41:52.209 --> 41:53.177 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
step.

41:53.210 --> 41:54.912 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, it does.

41:54.945 --> 41:57.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Everything you just said is sort
of your personal
experience of why you get out of
boxes.

41:57.147 --> 42:01.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But then you are extrapolating,
I think, to
a larger -- like, this is what
we all need.

42:01.952 --> 42:02.987 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is what America needs.

42:03.020 --> 42:03.988 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
W. KAMAU BELL: Yes.

42:04.021 --> 42:05.422 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes?

42:05.456 --> 42:07.224 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
W. KAMAU BELL: Yes, because I
travel around,
and I talk to people.

42:07.258 --> 42:11.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And everybody sort of loves
their part of
America, which is great, but
then a lot of

42:11.729 --> 42:15.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
times, we think, this is the
most America
part of America, the part I live
in.

42:15.366 --> 42:17.801 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Like, the people in New York
think, this is
the most America.

42:17.835 --> 42:19.003 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
People in Alabama think...

42:19.036 --> 42:20.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: To the detriment,
though, of
the culture?

42:20.838 --> 42:24.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
W. KAMAU BELL: Yes, because then
you watch
the news, and if you're in New
York and they

42:24.475 --> 42:29.813 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
say -- they talk about Alabama,
you think,
ah, that's not my country,
that's not my people.

42:29.847 --> 42:33.651 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so somehow you condescend to
what their
experience is, or you think you
can actually

42:33.684 --> 42:36.020 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
judge their experience, even
though you have
never been there.

42:36.053 --> 42:39.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, you think those people want
-- like, you
look at people in coal country,
people who

42:39.623 --> 42:42.826 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
don't live in coal country go,
why do they
want to destroy the environment
with coal?

42:42.860 --> 42:45.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But if you go talk to people in
coal country,
it's about jobs.

42:45.930 --> 42:48.499 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We sort of demonize them because
we think
they love destroying the
environment.

42:48.532 --> 42:51.101 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You talked to the
alt-right
leader, right, Richard Spencer.

42:51.135 --> 42:52.469 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
W. KAMAU BELL: Yes.

42:52.503 --> 42:56.707 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But you do it in
a gentle,
sort of humorous way.

42:56.740 --> 42:58.075 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's not like you're...

42:58.108 --> 43:00.744 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
W. KAMAU BELL: Yes, I do it the
same way I'm
talking to you, yes.

43:00.778 --> 43:01.745 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

43:01.779 --> 43:02.813 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

43:02.846 --> 43:04.615 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
But to what end?

43:04.648 --> 43:05.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You're not trying to convince
them -- and
you have -- and you're clear
about your own

43:05.549 --> 43:06.817 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
left-leaning, where you're
coming from.

43:06.850 --> 43:07.885 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
W. KAMAU BELL: Yes.

43:07.918 --> 43:09.286 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's not -- I'm not pulling a
trick on anybody.

43:09.320 --> 43:10.654 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I sit down as the person I am.

43:10.688 --> 43:12.723 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm very Googleable, so people
can find out
everything about me.

43:12.756 --> 43:14.058 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

43:14.091 --> 43:15.059 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
W. KAMAU BELL: And they're not
going to be
tricked about me.

43:15.092 --> 43:16.293 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Not only are you
Googleable.

43:16.327 --> 43:18.395 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You say it all right on the
cover of the book.

43:18.429 --> 43:19.396 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
W. KAMAU BELL: Yes.

43:19.430 --> 43:20.397 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I have written it down on paper.

43:20.431 --> 43:21.465 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's forever.

43:21.498 --> 43:22.499 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But the idea is like, can we
have a conversation?

43:22.533 --> 43:24.702 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Can we actually get to a
different place?

43:24.735 --> 43:28.105 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the thing that I'm doing on
TV is, like,
I know it's for TV.

43:28.138 --> 43:32.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if I talk to you and get you
relaxed and
make you laugh and I laugh,
you're going to

43:32.710 --> 43:34.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
say something that you weren't
expecting to
say, because you're more
comfortable.

43:34.912 --> 43:38.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Richard Spencer normally sits
across from
people like me, and they're
pushing him and

43:38.315 --> 43:39.283 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
they're challenging him.

43:39.316 --> 43:40.284 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And it makes him defensive.

43:40.317 --> 43:42.186 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it sort of gets to the same
place.

43:42.219 --> 43:45.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
By me sitting down with me, we
got to different
places than he normally gets
with other people,

43:45.623 --> 43:48.525 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which exposed him in a different
way to people
who thought they knew everything
about him.

43:48.559 --> 43:51.962 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The election
happened, surprised
a lot of people.

43:51.996 --> 43:58.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there was suddenly a lot of
talk about
an America that felt left
behind, right, or

43:58.769 --> 44:00.537 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
left out.

44:00.571 --> 44:04.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So to the extent you're clear
about where
you're coming from and your
politics, what

44:04.508 --> 44:08.479 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
do you think people of your
political persuasion
should be doing now?

44:08.512 --> 44:12.116 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
W. KAMAU BELL: I just wrote an
op-ed for The
New York Times saying people in
Berkeley need

44:12.149 --> 44:13.884 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to go vacation in Alabama.

44:13.917 --> 44:18.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that that is really --
if you can,
get out of your comfort zone and
get out of

44:18.155 --> 44:20.457 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
your immediate area and go
someplace you wouldn't
expect to go.

44:20.491 --> 44:22.092 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You are going to learn more
about people.

44:22.126 --> 44:23.861 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think people in Alabama
should go to
Berkeley.

44:23.894 --> 44:25.496 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I travel the country a lot.

44:25.529 --> 44:27.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you talk to people and
they're like, I
have never been to New York
City.

44:27.264 --> 44:28.465 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You have never been to New York
City?

44:28.499 --> 44:30.267 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now, I get a lot of that is
economic.

44:30.300 --> 44:32.603 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But some of that is just people
think, that's
not for me.

44:32.636 --> 44:35.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I feel like the best thing
you can do
in this country is mix it up
with other people.

44:35.339 --> 44:37.808 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, if you can't physically do
it, you need
to get online.

44:37.841 --> 44:39.777 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You need to connect with people.

44:39.810 --> 44:42.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You need to try to talk to
people, not yelling
at people on Facebook and
Twitter, but actually

44:42.780 --> 44:44.515 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
really connect with people.

44:44.548 --> 44:48.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Just one last
thing in thinking
about the comedy and the
sociopolitical.

44:48.786 --> 44:51.321 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Serious issues, you're dealing
with.

44:51.355 --> 44:52.556 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Is there a line?

44:52.589 --> 44:55.125 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is there someplace where you
think comedy
just can't go?

44:55.159 --> 44:58.395 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
W. KAMAU BELL: No, comedy is
pretty nonpartisan.

44:58.429 --> 45:00.397 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Comedy goes wherever comedy
wants to go.

45:00.431 --> 45:03.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Whether or not something is a
joke depends
on the ability of the person who
writes the

45:03.434 --> 45:05.069 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
joke to communicate the
punchline.

45:05.102 --> 45:07.604 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Comedy is not something that --
it's like
math.

45:07.638 --> 45:10.107 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's way more like math than
people realize.

45:10.140 --> 45:11.775 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There's comedians who are
Republicans.

45:11.809 --> 45:13.043 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There's comedians who are
Democrats.

45:13.077 --> 45:14.878 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Comedy doesn't care.

45:14.912 --> 45:17.081 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Comedy is just there to make
people laugh.

45:17.114 --> 45:20.451 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, "The
Awkward Thoughts
of W. Kamau Bell."

45:20.484 --> 45:22.219 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Thank you very much.

45:22.252 --> 45:28.959 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
W. KAMAU BELL: Thank you.

45:28.992 --> 45:36.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Tonight:
reflections from
author Brian Castner, who offers
his Humble

45:36.066 --> 45:41.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Opinion on why he felt most at
home overseas
fighting what he calls the
forever war.

45:41.839 --> 45:45.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRIAN CASTNER, Author, "The Long
Walk": It's
a little odd to be a veteran of
a war that

45:45.442 --> 45:46.810 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
doesn't end.

45:46.844 --> 45:49.947 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I did three tours, got home from
Iraq a decade
ago.

45:49.980 --> 45:53.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You think you have moved on, put
the war in
its place, and then you see
Tomahawk cruise

45:53.884 --> 45:58.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
missile strikes on cable news,
and you're
reminded that your war isn't
over.

45:58.122 --> 46:00.691 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's just gone on without you.

46:00.724 --> 46:05.929 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some of us call it the forever
war, the invasions
of Afghanistan and Iraq, bombing
Libya and

46:05.963 --> 46:12.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yemen, raids all over Africa,
and now Army
Rangers and Marine Corps
artillery in Syria.

46:12.336 --> 46:16.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's already the longest war in
American history,
and I have given up thinking
peace is coming

46:16.874 --> 46:18.709 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
any time soon.

46:18.742 --> 46:23.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our nation has an all-volunteer
military,
and people join for lots of
reasons: education,

46:23.747 --> 46:26.316 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a sense of adventure,
patriotism.

46:26.350 --> 46:31.622 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But staying in the military,
racking up five,
six, seven tours, that's a
different kind

46:31.655 --> 46:33.423 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of decision.

46:33.457 --> 46:36.760 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are plenty of ways to pay
for college
that don't involve getting shot
at over and

46:36.794 --> 46:38.328 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
over again.

46:38.362 --> 46:39.563 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So why did I do it?

46:39.596 --> 46:43.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Why do soldiers choose to keep
serving in
the forever war?

46:43.433 --> 46:48.639 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I was an explosive ordnance
disposal technician,
EOD, we call it, the bomb squad.

46:48.672 --> 46:52.342 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
After my last Iraq tour, I was
worn out mentally
and physically.

46:52.376 --> 46:56.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But my EOD brothers and sisters
were dying,
and I needed to stay to protect
them.

46:56.947 --> 47:04.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Such a feeling provides intense
meaning, but
also, in the forever war,
limitless obligation.

47:04.655 --> 47:09.059 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our little tribe has lost more
than its share,
disarming those infamous
roadside bombs, and

47:09.092 --> 47:15.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I found it harder to stop going
back than
to go the first time, because,
at its core,

47:15.499 --> 47:18.735 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
EOD work is about lifesaving,
not killing.

47:18.769 --> 47:24.441 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How do you say, I'm too tired, I
can't help
anyone else?

47:24.474 --> 47:28.545 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a devil's bargain, choosing
between one's
tribe and one's family.

47:28.579 --> 47:32.549 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On the one hand, I needed to be
in Iraq to
keep my comrades alive.

47:32.583 --> 47:37.254 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, on the other, every moment
I was gone,
I wasn't a good husband or dad.

47:37.287 --> 47:43.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Sometimes, I ask myself, how
many tours would
have been enough to know, deep
in my bones,

47:43.460 --> 47:45.329 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that I had done my part?

47:45.362 --> 47:48.465 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This isn't survivor's guilt, or
nostalgia
for the adrenaline.

47:48.498 --> 47:51.635 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That is just shallow, fades with
youth.

47:51.668 --> 47:58.575 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a haunting sense that I let
my comrades
down by giving up before the job
was done.

47:58.609 --> 48:03.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But that's the paradox, right,
because it
feels like this business will
never be finished.

48:03.747 --> 48:09.319 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For years, I maintained this
fantasy that
I would get a phone call from my
old unit.

48:09.353 --> 48:11.488 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We need you back, they'd say.

48:11.521 --> 48:16.660 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I kept all my gear packed in a
trunk in the
basement, just in case.

48:16.693 --> 48:18.829 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I don't want to go back to Iraq.

48:18.862 --> 48:22.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
But I also don't want my
brothers and sisters
to go back without me.

48:22.299 --> 48:27.971 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The end of the forever war can't
come soon
enough.

48:28.005 --> 48:38.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now to our
"NewsHour" Shares,
something that caught our eye
that may be

48:38.582 --> 48:40.617 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
