48:40.651 --> 48:45.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the aftermath of the terror
attack in Manchester,
England, writer Anthony
Breznican took to

48:45.289 --> 48:51.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Twitter to recount how one
person comforted
him during a difficult period in
his own life.

48:51.161 --> 48:54.398 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That man was Fred Rogers, of
"Mister Rogers'
Neighborhood."

48:54.431 --> 48:58.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Breznican recently spoke with us
via Skype
about the lessons he learned
during a chance

48:58.535 --> 49:00.871 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
encounter with the late TV icon.

49:00.904 --> 49:10.781 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ANTHONY BREZNICAN,
"Entertainment Weekly":
My grandfather had died not so
long ago, and

49:10.814 --> 49:15.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he was sort of this one steady
constant in
my life, and a really positive
influence.

49:15.285 --> 49:20.657 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when you don't have a lot of
those to
being with, to lose one is
really devastating.

49:20.691 --> 49:23.827 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, I was going through a hard
time.

49:23.860 --> 49:30.367 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One afternoon, or morning, I was
leaving the
dorm, and I heard a familiar
song coming down

49:30.400 --> 49:33.170 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the hallway, won't you be my
neighbor.

49:33.203 --> 49:38.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I kind of stuck my head into
the commons
room, and there on the TV was
Mr. Rogers.

49:38.408 --> 49:41.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of his favorite things was
to talk about,
what do you do with the mad that
you feel?

49:41.912 --> 49:44.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED ROGERS, Host, "Mister
Rogers' Neighborhood"
(singing): What do you do with
the mad that

49:44.848 --> 49:47.985 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
feel, when you feel so mad, you
could bite?

49:48.018 --> 49:53.023 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANTHONY BREZNICAN: You know, a
way of helping
kids deal with their anger,
acknowledging

49:53.056 --> 49:55.392 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it, instead of telling them that
they shouldn't
feel it.

49:55.425 --> 49:59.396 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it was like, this speaks to
me.

49:59.429 --> 50:00.397 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I'm very angry.

50:00.430 --> 50:01.865 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I'm very scared.

50:01.898 --> 50:04.935 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Even as a young adult, like this
-- it didn't
feel like a kids program.

50:04.968 --> 50:06.703 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It felt very profound.

50:06.737 --> 50:11.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Within about two weeks or so, I
was at the
school paper and I got into the
elevator to

50:11.408 --> 50:16.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
go down to the lobby, and the
doors opened,
and standing there is Mr. Rogers
himself.

50:16.780 --> 50:22.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I turned around and said, like:
"Look, I just
want to tell you how much you
mean to me."

50:22.285 --> 50:26.423 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he said -- he didn't say
like, thank you,
I appreciate that or anything.

50:26.456 --> 50:30.127 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was just like: "Oh, did you
grow up as
one of my television neighbors?"

50:30.160 --> 50:32.229 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And just the way he said it was
so sweet.

50:32.262 --> 50:35.098 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I was like, "Yes, yes, I was
your neighbor."

50:35.132 --> 50:39.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he gives -- opens his arms
and he is like,
"It's great to see you again,
neighbor," and

50:39.403 --> 50:41.071 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
he just gives me this big hug.

50:41.104 --> 50:48.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it felt so wonderful to meet
him, but
also to literally be embraced by
Mr. Rogers,

50:48.078 --> 50:49.279 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
this kind man.

50:49.312 --> 50:52.549 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRED ROGERS (singing): I will be
back when
the day was new.

50:52.582 --> 50:56.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANTHONY BREZNICAN: And he sat
down and he
said, "Would you like to tell me
what it was

50:56.286 --> 50:57.788 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
